WEBVTT

00:03.355 --> 00:04.818
So really, that's caused no problem. And I think 
you'll see a higher percentage of women coming

00:04.958 --> 00:14.356
into reserve program and the Air Force in general 
in the future than you have in the past. Are there

00:15.017 --> 00:25.718
some parallels between women coming into the 
military and the reserves and women being allowed

00:15.017 --> 00:25.718
here at A&M back in the 1960s? I don't really see 
any. Well, it's parallels as far as attitudes,

00:27.118 --> 00:31.623
initial resistance, which has changed. Oh, OK. I 
would presume so. I would presume so. But here,

00:36.689 --> 00:42.976
once again, after you get used to the idea and you 
see that it's going to work, then you accept it. So

00:44.618 --> 00:48.443
there could be some parallels there, but I never 
thought of it in that context. OK. Let's talk. I'd

00:49.724 --> 00:50.365
like to talk. I went over a number of your 
appointments. and duties here. And I'd like to

00:57.162 --> 01:04.396
talk about the development of the Air Force 
Reserve in the Bryan College Station area. It

01:04.416 --> 01:10.408
looks like there was the 9807 ARS and then the 9412 
ARS. Could you explain that development? I think

01:13.893 --> 01:22.585
at that particular time, that was more or less a 
change in designation of an activity more than an

01:13.893 --> 01:22.585
actual change in the mission or scope of the 
activity. They were shuffling numbers like mad

01:22.605 --> 01:25.229
back in those times. But as I recall, I don't recall 
there being any particular change. I will say that

01:32.579 --> 01:42.432
in all of those time periods, the reserve program 
was nothing more than not much more than a paper

01:43.171 --> 01:45.254
exercise and paperwork. We had no equipment. We 
had very little realistic training. Our training

01:52.907 --> 02:03.785
consisted of taking correspondence courses in 
particular areas and trying to keep up what we call

01:52.907 --> 02:03.785
our general military training. There are certain 
things that we have to go through annually, such as

02:09.867 --> 02:20.283
The Uniform Code of Military Justice, we have to be 
familiar with that, not only so that we can watch

02:09.867 --> 02:20.283
other people, but so that we ourselves will know 
how to conduct ourselves under certain

02:09.867 --> 02:20.283
circumstances.

02:21.484 --> 02:33.042
Things like communication security that we have 
to review every year to refresh on our minds that

02:21.484 --> 02:33.042
there are certain things you don't talk about on 
the telephone. Those types of things, we were able

02:35.145 --> 02:37.528
to get those out of the way. But as far as real gut 
training, to qualify us to go into an active duty

02:39.837 --> 02:42.801
situation. It was almost nonexistent in those 
days. Now, let's clarify. When were those days?

02:49.569 --> 02:54.455
When was the first Air Force Reserve unit in this 
area? I don't know, because it was here before I

02:55.196 --> 02:58.019
came in. I went into the Air Force Reserves in this 
area in about 1960 or 61, as I recall. After I got off

03:04.046 --> 03:07.971
of active duty in 1956, I was living in the Waco 
area. and was assigned to a couple of units up in

03:08.153 --> 03:10.996
that area. They were larger units, but they were 
primarily, once again, where we would meet and do

03:11.016 --> 03:21.486
the best we could with correspondence courses and 
lectures and talks. But we had no field training.

03:25.910 --> 03:27.011
We had no airplanes. We had no equipment. When I 
came from Waco here in probably 1959, 1960, in that

03:29.473 --> 03:36.540
time frame, I immediately aligned with a reserve 
unit here locally, and I've even forgotten the

03:37.128 --> 03:42.235
number, but it would be the first unit that we had. 
9807. 9807, yes, okay. I found the same conditions

03:45.739 --> 03:52.668
to be true here that existed in Waco, and that is no 
equipment. We, of course, all of us wore uniforms,

03:52.808 --> 04:06.966
and we spent a great deal of time on military 
courtesy and chain of command, span of control,

03:52.808 --> 04:06.966
all those kinds of things that are basic to any 
organization, military or otherwise. We had the

04:07.773 --> 04:08.794
nucleus. We had the people that wanted to do it.

04:13.802 --> 04:28.002
And then after that, I really guess when the thing 
turned around for me, and when the reserves turned

04:13.802 --> 04:28.002
around, and you can find the date on it, was my first 
duty assignment at Ellington Air Force Base. And I

04:28.022 --> 04:29.444
believe that was in the 9-25th? That was 9-25th. 
Tag at Ellington. Any of these initials you need me

04:37.793 --> 04:40.898
to clarify for you, I can do that. That's Tactical 
Airlift Group. They had 119s. That was the first

04:44.464 --> 04:45.947
unit I was ever in. 1967 to 1969. They had real 
airplanes, and they would fly. And I'd never been

04:51.857 --> 04:54.521
in a unit that had airplanes before. From that 
point, it got better and better and better until

04:55.403 --> 04:58.508
today. Our airplanes will match active-duty 
airplanes any day of the week. as far as quality of

05:05.148 --> 05:10.075
maintenance and flyability and the people that 
know how to fly them and how to fight. In other

05:11.057 --> 05:16.685
words, from 1967 on down, you've been getting new 
airplanes? No. No. Are you getting the airplanes

05:18.348 --> 05:27.161
that come from the active duty and they decided 
they get the new ones and you get their sort of

05:18.348 --> 05:27.161
hand-me-downs? We have an Air Force base in 
Arizona near Phoenix called Davis-Monthan Air

05:27.461 --> 05:31.668
Force Base. It's otherwise known as the Boneyard 
of the Air Force. When the Air Force can no longer

05:34.713 --> 05:39.580
fly an airplane, they send it to the boneyard. You 
use it for spare parts or for whatever. Well,

05:42.364 --> 05:50.316
instead of sending it to Davis-Monthan, when they 
couldn't get another mile out of it, then they gave

05:42.364 --> 05:50.316
it to the reserves, and then we'd squeeze some more 
miles out of it. That was the beginning. That's the

05:52.079 --> 05:54.963
way the 119s worked. When about did that start? 
That's a significant change. That happened

05:58.629 --> 06:01.513
probably in about 19... 1958, 1959, when we 
started getting those kinds of airplanes. Now

06:06.753 --> 06:08.835
here, once again, I'm relying strictly on my 
memory. That's fine. Now, I could be off 10 years

06:09.556 --> 06:14.022
one way or the other. But this is when I first had 
knowledge of it, to put it that way. But then, we've

06:19.009 --> 06:23.354
always gotten our equipment from the active duty. 
As they would get better equipment, we'd get their

06:23.575 --> 06:26.318
older equipment. But the quality of the equipment 
we get has constantly improved So that now, for

06:32.206 --> 06:42.101
example, in Vietnam and since then, the F-4 has 
been one of our primary fighter aircraft, fighter

06:32.206 --> 06:42.101
bombers, primarily a fighter. All of our units 
have F-4s now. Now, the F-105 was the plane we had

06:46.327 --> 06:52.977
prior to that, which was an excellent airplane, 
still an excellent airplane. But the F-4 is coming

06:52.997 --> 06:56.021
in to take its place. Plus, we've got a unit at Hill 
Air Force Base now.

07:03.222 --> 07:06.405
getting F-16s right off the assembly line, 
getting ready to. So now the reserve groups are

07:07.346 --> 07:11.291
getting brand new equipment. It's never been 
flown before. And is that since the Reagan

07:13.153 --> 07:15.355
administration? Yes. Is that part of the changes, 
do you think, of the Reagan administration? Part

07:21.041 --> 07:23.904
of the increasing defense expenditure? I would 
say that it's a result of the overall realization

07:23.924 --> 07:31.272
that we cannot afford from a fiscal standpoint to 
maintain the kind of active duty air force that we

07:32.602 --> 07:39.089
need to defend the country. But we recognize that 
we have to have certain squares filled in order to

07:40.911 --> 07:45.956
be able to support our various war plans. And so if 
you don't have the money to support those war plans

07:47.097 --> 08:02.153
with active duty forces, then you spend the money 
on the reserves because you can maintain a group or

07:47.097 --> 08:02.153
a wing of reserve aircraft at a fraction of the cost 
that it would cost to maintain an active duty

08:02.437 --> 08:05.581
outfit because of the fact that they work all day 
every day. Sure. Of course, your primary cost,

08:06.021 --> 08:11.648
once you get the equipment cost behind you, you've 
got to have the equipment, whether it's active

08:06.021 --> 08:11.648
duty or reserve. But then once you put that to one 
side, then your payroll cost is your biggest

08:12.229 --> 08:17.436
single cost. And of course, the reservist 
paycheck is a fraction of what an active duty

08:18.497 --> 08:23.903
paycheck would be. But yet, he can meet the same 
standards, the same flying criteria, can fill the

08:24.364 --> 08:31.633
same square in a war plane that an active duty guy 
can fill. So that's why the shift. It's a matter of

08:33.769 --> 08:37.794
we can't afford the kind of active duty force we 
really need. Therefore, this is the alternative

08:37.814 --> 08:40.937
we're accepting. I think it would have come no 
matter who the president had been. We got a bigger

08:46.883 --> 08:52.128
pie, but the pie is not big enough, so the reserves 
are getting a bigger piece of the bigger pie. Oh,

08:52.548 --> 08:53.689
OK. OK. So the Air Force itself has come to this 
realization. Oh, yes. Yes. It's referred to

09:01.803 --> 09:04.367
primarily as a total force policy. And that is a 
major concept. The active duty have always, it's

09:07.512 --> 09:13.682
almost like the acceptance of minorities or 
women. They've always kind of looked down their

09:13.702 --> 09:18.530
nose at reservists as being second-class 
citizens.

09:20.533 --> 09:27.625
Because back in the old days, when we were called 
the ragtag militia, uniforms were tattered the

09:29.039 --> 09:55.131
haircuts were bad shoes were you know well those 
are personal things it was all taken work real hard

09:29.039 --> 09:55.131
at improving the image of the reservist and it's 
paid off i think the active duty force looks at us as

09:29.039 --> 09:55.131
an equal partner in the defense establishment as 
opposed to a second class group of citizens and so

09:29.039 --> 09:55.131
that's why those of us in positions to to manage 
other people when we find, especially at the full

09:55.499 --> 10:13.505
colonel position and above, we look at our people 
much more severely properly than anyone else does

09:55.499 --> 10:13.505
to make sure that when we put a guy in a full 
colonel's position or in a BG position that he's

09:55.499 --> 10:13.505
going to be a credit to the rest of us. Now tell me 
about this total forest policy. When did it become

10:18.172 --> 10:21.377
a volunteer? I would say Once again, I'm going to 
have to pull a figure out of the air. Sure. But I

10:26.747 --> 10:39.338
would say the total force policy has been 
established as an official policy of the Air

10:26.747 --> 10:39.338
Force, Department of the Air Force, for 
approximately 10 years, 8 to 10 years. It's a

10:39.458 --> 10:41.059
relatively new concept.

10:43.582 --> 10:53.670
All the total force policy does is to recognize the 
reserve forces as an integral part of the defense

10:43.582 --> 10:53.670
establishment and as an integral part in 
supporting our war plans. Always before, the war

10:56.377 --> 11:00.021
plans were supported exclusively by the active 
duty forces. Now the reserves are plowed right in

11:00.762 --> 11:07.109
and cranked right in to the requirements to 
support war plans. So that if we execute plan

11:07.129 --> 11:15.599
so-and-so and it calls for so many F4 units, bang, 
they're activated and there they go, just like an

11:07.129 --> 11:15.599
active duty outfit. That's fantastic.

11:21.376 --> 11:22.617
Interesting. Yeah, it sure is interesting. I want 
to talk about the change and the status of the local

11:25.621 --> 11:35.671
Air Force Reserve units. We started this 
conversation a little bit ago about the history of

11:35.752 --> 11:39.976
it. How has it changed? And what's the chain of 
command? If a young man wants to get into the Air

11:43.580 --> 11:48.966
Force Reserve here, what's the chain of command 
today? And what's the status? Actually, at the

11:51.498 --> 11:57.444
time I went to Ellington Air Force Base was when the 
local Air Force Reserve unit was phased out. We

11:57.724 --> 12:02.128
have no local Air Force Reserve units here in the 
College Station Bryan area. And since then, the

12:02.148 --> 12:07.713
Ellington Air Force Base unit has been 
transferred to Bergstrom Air Force Base at

12:02.148 --> 12:07.713
Austin, Texas. There is no Air Force Reserve unit 
in Houston, the largest metropolitan area in the

12:08.294 --> 12:14.920
United States, without an Air Force Reserve unit. 
Now, let me back up and say one thing that needs to be

12:15.901 --> 12:19.564
said. When I'm talking about Air Force Reserve, 
well, there are two terms that let me clarify.

12:27.736 --> 12:29.578
There's what we call Air Reserve Forces. When you 
hear the term Air Reserve Forces, you're talking

12:30.719 --> 12:36.846
about Air Force Reserves and Air National Guard. 
That's the Air Reserve Forces is all of the Reserve

12:37.767 --> 12:41.952
Forces. Now, I've not talked about Guard because I 
know very little about the Air Force National

12:41.972 --> 12:48.319
Guard, the Air National Guard. As you know, during 
peacetime, they're under the jurisdiction of the

12:48.907 --> 12:52.831
governor of the various states. During wartime, 
they're nationalized, then they become a

12:52.851 --> 12:56.295
national resource. The guard units are plowed 
into the warplanes just the way Air Force Reserve

12:57.136 --> 13:03.042
units are. They do have an Air National Guard unit 
in Houston, but not an Air Force Reserve unit. So if

13:09.029 --> 13:14.574
a young man wanted to get in the Air Force Reserve 
here, chances are his best bet would be at Austin.

13:15.375 --> 13:16.416
Now, we... The... United States is divided up into 
what we call three numbered air forces. They're

13:22.949 --> 13:24.331
not geographical areas. They're divided up by 
weapon systems. There's a fourth air force, which

13:27.415 --> 13:36.769
is a numbered air force commanded by a two-star 
reserve general located at Sacramento,

13:27.415 --> 13:36.769
California, at McClellan Air Force Base. There's 
10th Air Force, which is commanded also, all these

13:36.789 --> 13:40.675
are commanded by two-star generals. As I 
mentioned, it was the highest rank that an air

13:41.275 --> 13:47.905
force reservist can hold under present law at 
Bergstrom Air Force Base. And then there's 14th

13:48.374 --> 14:01.833
Air Force, which is,

13:48.374 --> 14:01.833
what is, my mind's gone blank on where the 14th Air 
Force is located. Oh, we can fill it in later. Okay,

14:04.036 --> 14:04.977
it'll come to me. But in any event, those air forces 
primarily are divided up by weapons systems. Now

14:12.387 --> 14:16.373
the 4th and the 14th on the west coast and the east 
coast primarily have tactical airlift aircraft.

14:18.430 --> 14:19.792
In other words, they have the C-130s. Basically, 
the C-130 is their airplane right now for hauling

14:21.574 --> 14:24.898
things. The 14th has things east of the 
Mississippi. The 4th has things west of the

14:28.041 --> 14:31.906
Mississippi, all the units in those areas. 
Whereas 10th Air Force, the headquarters at

14:31.926 --> 14:41.437
Bergstrom Air Force Base, the one I was assigned to 
for so many years, well, previously it was at

14:31.926 --> 14:41.437
Ellington called Central Air Force Reserve 
Region. It was transferred to Bergstrom and

14:41.878 --> 14:46.123
re-designated 10th Air Force. has all the 
fighters and aircraft that are primarily gained

14:46.407 --> 14:55.000
by tactical air command. Also, we have all the 
aircraft that are gained by strategic air

14:55.882 --> 15:01.450
command, which includes your KC-135 tankers. 
We're getting into the KC-10 tanker now at

15:01.871 --> 15:05.416
Barksdale Air Force Base. All those assets are 
gained by strategic air command. 10th Air Force

15:11.606 --> 15:13.849
had responsibility for those units. Do you have 
any B-1 bombers? No, no B-1s online yet. Do you have

15:19.796 --> 15:20.757
any B-52s? No, not in the reserve program. KC-135 
is the tanker, which is a refueler for the B-52s.

15:30.186 --> 15:31.988
It's the heaviest thing we've gotten into yet. Do 
you think eventually you'll all get some bombers?

15:37.574 --> 15:38.335
It's hard to say. Strategic Air Command... has 
such a quick response time in the matter of minutes

15:41.099 --> 15:47.788
that I'm not sure reservists will ever man the 
bombers at B-52. That's absolutely true. Because

15:49.550 --> 15:53.476
we have to respond in 24 hours. SAC can't live with 
that kind of response. No, absolutely. It's 25

15:56.580 --> 15:58.723
minutes from Moscow to . That's right. That's 
true. But I really don't think you'll ever see any

16:01.486 --> 16:08.676
reserve

16:01.486 --> 16:08.676
bomber crews. There was a lot of hesitancy on 
whether we could ever handle a reserve tanker

16:09.685 --> 16:27.627
operation, but that seemed to be working 
relatively well because you've got more lead time

16:09.685 --> 16:27.627
on tankers than you have on bombers and what have 
you. But if someone in this area wanted to get in the

16:27.647 --> 16:32.273
reserve program, he would go to Berkshire Air 
Force Base. Now, 10th Air Force is the

16:32.453 --> 16:35.277
headquarters command. It's a giant paper mill. It 
has no airplanes itself. It manages a lot of units

16:38.558 --> 16:42.023
all over the United States that have airplanes. 
One of the units, the 924th, used to be the 924th

16:42.464 --> 16:47.632
Tactical Airlift Group. I don't know what the new 
designation was. They've renumbered it since I

16:49.215 --> 16:51.739
was there. It is located at Bergstrom Air Force 
Base. So that would be the place for a young man to

16:55.244 --> 16:58.049
go. Now, every base has what they call a reserve, an 
air reserve management officer, an ARMO.

17:05.500 --> 17:07.283
Basically, he's usually a master sergeant. our 
senior master sergeant, and he kind of keeps an eye

17:07.600 --> 17:14.188
on all the reserve slots on that base. So it's a 
single point of contact that a young man can go say,

17:14.208 --> 17:18.714
hey, I live over at Collin Station. I'm interested 
in getting a reserve program. Is there anything

17:20.497 --> 17:21.618
here for me? He knows where all the vacancies are, 
what all the skill requirements are, and he can

17:22.339 --> 17:30.549
help place individuals that have an interest in 
it. I'm wondering about the relationship that you

17:30.569 --> 17:35.576
have with the Air National Guard. Very little. 
