17:39.152 --> 17:53.332
level, the two-star general in charge of the 
National Guard, General Conaway, General John

17:39.152 --> 17:53.332
Conaway, and our boss, General Sandy Gill, Air 
Force Reserve General, probably live together.

17:53.893 --> 17:54.995
They're together all the time. But below that 
level, we don't really have much to do with each

17:55.575 --> 17:58.920
other. Our paths just don't cross that much. Is 
there friction between the two groups? No, not

18:04.027 --> 18:04.728
really. Not really. Well, I've heard that, or I 
have heard from some reservists, that while they

18:06.275 --> 18:19.513
are National Guard, they're just a bunch of 
political appointee types, and they're not

18:06.275 --> 18:19.513
really the military, and they're just good old 
boys. Would you respond to them? I will say that the

18:21.896 --> 18:32.130
National Guard has a tremendous political impact 
on this nation, more so than the Reserves.

18:34.253 --> 18:38.999
primarily because of the fact that they can exert 
pressure through the various governors of the

18:34.253 --> 18:38.999
state. I think it's a matter that

18:40.381 --> 18:56.562
they've just been at it longer than we have, and 
they've honed to perfection

18:40.381 --> 18:56.562
their abilities to muster political force when 
it's needed.

18:59.967 --> 19:03.872
Obviously, the military is prohibited from 
participating in any political activity. But

19:04.240 --> 19:15.671
when we're wearing our civilian clothes, like 
today, we're civilians, and we can call our

19:04.240 --> 19:15.671
congressman, ride the president, do whatever we 
want to as civilians. And we can express an

19:16.232 --> 19:22.738
interest in things pertaining to the military, 
whereas an active duty guy cannot do that. So I

19:23.779 --> 19:32.408
think the active duty force recognizes the 
reserve as the only shot they have at playing

19:23.779 --> 19:32.408
politics. They don't use that in a direct way. But 
through our knowing and our proximity to the

19:39.026 --> 19:58.010
military and knowing what some of our crying needs 
are, there's nothing that prevents us as

19:39.026 --> 19:58.010
individuals of picking up a phone and calling our 
congressman or when Phil Graham comes to town to

19:39.026 --> 19:58.010
see him and say, boy, we sure need some support and 
some aircraft spares because we're hurting bad.

19:58.331 --> 20:02.496
Well, that brings up an interesting point, the 
active duty people. perhaps using or mobilizing

20:02.999 --> 20:09.029
the reservists to put pressure on Washington. Is 
there, without naming names, of course, has there

20:09.129 --> 20:27.460
been in your career any attempt for active duty 
officers to say, OK, you reservists, maybe at your

20:09.129 --> 20:27.460
two-week camp or something like that, OK, you 
reservists, go home and write your congressman

20:09.129 --> 20:27.460
about this or that? Has there ever been any 
examples like that? I've never heard of it

20:29.847 --> 20:31.089
happening. And in fact, the active duty goes out of 
its way to make sure that that never happens

20:31.389 --> 20:39.739
because it's not proper.

20:42.683 --> 20:49.591
Now, that's not to say that a lot of reservists 
don't do exactly the things that the active duty

20:42.683 --> 20:49.591
would like to see us do. But it's not done at the 
request or at the direction of the active duty.

20:52.475 --> 20:58.082
It's a self-initiated thing that reservists see a 
need because of their proximity to the situation.

20:58.450 --> 21:02.395
and try to do something about it in their civilian 
capacity. Yeah, I wouldn't think that would be.

