small, the risk was there. And some of them didn't 
choose to take the risk. The minute the draft was

23:06.489 --> 23:14.919
dropped and it became all volunteer, then there 
was not the threat of the draft. So therefore, they

23:14.959 --> 23:17.422
didn't need to seek an alternative. So it had a 
definite impact on our recruiting. I would say

23:20.808 --> 23:25.196
that the impact was relatively short lived.

23:26.358 --> 23:40.402
I sense, and I think I've talked to a number of other 
people that sense, that there's a kind of a rebirth

23:26.358 --> 23:40.402
of nationalism in this country, that there seems 
to be almost a wave of patriotism sweeping the

23:26.358 --> 23:40.402
country that's been absent for a long time. I think 
it's kind of a digging out the quagmire of Vietnam.

23:47.082 --> 24:02.683
At the time, the Vietnamese situation was going 
and up to and immediately after the cessation of

23:47.082 --> 24:02.683
hostilities, I would say that the military was at 
an all-time low in this country in the eyes of the

23:47.082 --> 24:02.683
citizen on the street. It was almost an insult to be 
in a uniform. I've been in airports and in public

24:06.288 --> 24:14.018
places in my uniform where people would people 
would drive by in the car and yell obscenities to

24:14.673 --> 24:18.257
you. No kidding. Instead of being- Was that at the 
end of the war? Early 70s? Yeah, in that time

24:22.643 --> 24:24.024
period. As a result, we're encouraged never to 
wear a uniform, especially a general officer

24:25.066 --> 24:34.097
never wears a uniform when he's going public 
transportation or what have you. No kidding. We

24:34.637 --> 24:40.244
always go in civilian clothes because, first of 
all- That's a response? That's a response of the

24:40.364 --> 24:43.669
post-Vietnam era? That- plus the increasing 
instance of terrorism. Now, not so much in this

24:48.619 --> 24:51.864
country, but overseas. You've made the General 
Dozier instance and things of that type. They

24:57.292 --> 25:05.244
don't like you to play up the fact that you're a 
general officer. In fact, I've worn this pin ever

25:06.225 --> 25:11.393
since my little tie pin with my star ever since I was 
promoted. Most of the general officers have a

25:11.913 --> 25:18.779
bumper sticker on the car with the number of stars 
that you're entitled to. First of all, because

25:18.839 --> 25:27.026
they give you preferred parking places at certain 
places, like from the officer's club, you know,

25:18.839 --> 25:27.026
you've got a reserved general officer, little 
bennies that go with it. But they're even talking

25:27.706 --> 25:38.435
now about eliminating those because they don't 
want you to be known as a general officer because of

25:27.706 --> 25:38.435
the potential for terrorist kidnapping or what 
have you. What does that do to morale? Well, you

25:40.177 --> 25:41.818
know, it's kind of... I mean, you've worked this 
long, and now you can't even wear your uniform.

25:48.693 --> 25:51.896
That really hasn't come into being yet. There's 
just some talk about it. I do know that they've

25:54.398 --> 25:59.543
issued bumper stickers now with the capital 
letter G on it instead of the star. Of course, it

25:59.623 --> 26:02.646
doesn't take very many brains to figure out what 
the G stands for.

26:05.428 --> 26:11.434
But it's not critical in this country, but in an 
overseas assignment, you have to assume that

26:11.920 --> 26:17.346
someone's trying to kill you or kidnap you all the 
time if you're a general officer. And it's not a bad

26:17.366 --> 26:20.609
assumption because it's true in a lot of places. 
Yeah. But here, when you're on public

26:22.912 --> 26:29.659
transportation, here, do you wear your uniform 
when you don't? No. And that's Air Force

26:30.440 --> 26:31.781
directive? Well, it's Air Force policy. I don't 
think there's anything in writing. It's just that

26:35.666 --> 26:40.611
when we have meetings, and we have meetings twice a 
year of all Air Force Reserve general officers,

26:40.979 --> 26:45.125
And they're mirrors almost of some of the active 
duty general officer meetings that they have.

26:46.467 --> 26:52.355
We're told that it's Air Force policy that you not 
travel in your military uniform on public

26:46.467 --> 26:52.355
conveyance. And when you travel in military 
aircraft, of course, then you have to have on

26:52.996 --> 26:56.341
uniform. But if you're riding public 
transportation, airplanes, trains, buses, you

26:56.581 --> 27:02.450
never travel in uniform. They even discourage 
full colonels from doing it. But general

27:05.133 --> 27:06.936
officers, you just don't do it. And it's because of 
the fact that you're going to get heckled by

27:07.658 --> 27:17.669
certain elements, not so much now as immediately 
right after the Vietnamese. But you know, it's

27:18.150 --> 27:28.001
almost unbelievable that someone in the uniform 
of their country, trying to serve their country,

27:18.150 --> 27:28.001
would be heckled for having that uniform on. I 
know. But it happens. I know.

27:33.764 --> 27:36.329
It's incredible, just a little aside here. But as I 
mentioned, that's when we hit rock bottom. And I

27:42.880 --> 27:45.024
think it's continued to improve since then. And I 
think that this country is on the verge of giving a

27:45.345 --> 27:58.388
lot of respect and having a lot of patriotic fervor 
that we've not had for years. I think that Reagan

27:59.684 --> 28:05.213
has really got his hands full on what he's going to 
do in Central and South America. I think that

28:05.233 --> 28:18.233
without any question in my mind, the threat in 
Central and South America is at least as

28:05.233 --> 28:18.233
substantial as Nazi Germany's threat during the 
Second World War and maybe worse because of its

28:05.233 --> 28:18.233
proximity to our country. To me, that threat far 
overshadows anything that Korea or Vietnam could

28:19.675 --> 28:24.062
have ever done to us. To me, this is the single most 
serious threat to our survival as a country that I

28:28.928 --> 28:36.298
can imagine. And yet we've got people in Congress 
right now that are saying, let those people work

28:36.318 --> 28:42.987
out their own problems. And it just doesn't work 
that way. Well, let's talk a little bit more about

28:46.092 --> 28:50.778
the draft and the volunteer army. And you have to 
forgive me for chasing these rabbits when they

28:51.519 --> 28:54.123
come. Oh, that's fine. I want your ideas and your 
opinions. I want your ideas on the draft. Do you

29:02.501 --> 29:04.363
think that we should reinstate the draft? Without 
any question, I'd do it before noon today if I had

29:04.663 --> 29:07.586
the authority. I see no reason why a certain 
segment of our society should defend this country

29:08.427 --> 29:16.296
and another segment, because of their affluence, 
never have to do it. I think that people from all

29:17.357 --> 29:28.028
walks of life should serve this country equally, 
either voluntarily or if they have to be made to do

29:17.357 --> 29:28.028
it, then let's make them do it. But we all know that

29:28.953 --> 29:38.284
the people in the lower economic stratus make up 
the bulk of the military. By the same token, you

29:39.005 --> 29:50.258
don't have that vast cross-section and the 
thinking and the expertise of a good

29:39.005 --> 29:50.258
cross-section of the country that we had during 
the draft. You've got a distorted view of what the

29:50.999 --> 29:56.646
world's all about because you're drawing from 
only one segment of the society. And I'm speaking

29:56.666 --> 29:58.588
primarily of the enlisted corps now. The officer 
corps, I think, you've got a pretty good cross

29:59.058 --> 30:02.403
section. The officer corps is pretty well 
educated, more so than the regular society,

30:03.364 --> 30:10.475
because you've got to have a college degree. And I 
would say that with rare exceptions, you'll never

30:10.575 --> 30:20.110
see anybody reach the rank of full colonel or above 
without a master's degree. For general officers,

30:20.550 --> 30:25.077
it's becoming more common that you have a PhD to 
become a general officer. And I don't have one, but

30:25.097 --> 30:27.681
I think in the future, That's almost going to be 
part of one of the squares to fill. But I don't think

30:31.517 --> 30:36.943
you'll ever see a full colonel, very many full 
colonels in the future without a master's degree.

30:38.385 --> 30:44.952
To me, this relates fairly well with what happens 
in the civilian segment of our society, not so in

30:38.385 --> 30:44.952
the enlisted grades. So back to your original 
question, I can't tell you how strongly I feel that

30:46.474 --> 30:52.541
we should reinstate the draft, even in peacetime. 
Now, it sounds to me that you see the draft more as

30:58.576 --> 31:07.468
Oh,

30:58.576 --> 31:07.468
something to increase the amount of citizenship. 
Absolutely. I think it's a civic responsibility

31:08.570 --> 31:11.914
to defend this country. And you also see it in 
class, as far as class terms. That is, the middle

31:17.802 --> 31:20.747
and the upper middle class. And upper class is a 
college, a suburban class. They don't have to

31:23.731 --> 31:25.693
serve, but others do. And you think that's unfair. 
I think it's unfair in that, first of all, I think

31:27.263 --> 31:35.173
every citizen has an obligation to do their share. 
But second of all, I think once people get into the

31:36.055 --> 31:41.422
military, that they themselves get something 
from it. I think those people are being deprived of

31:41.502 --> 31:47.209
the privilege of serving their country. And so I 
know a lot of people that say, boy, I would have

31:47.329 --> 31:53.878
never volunteered for that, but I'm sure glad I had 
the experience. And so you put someone in the

31:54.972 --> 32:00.919
position where they have to perform, and then 
later on, they're proud they had the experience.

32:01.259 --> 32:03.682
And they would not have done it had they not been 
made to do it. But I think that there's just no

32:04.803 --> 32:13.554
question whatsoever in my mind of, first of all, us 
having a better military if we did it that way.

32:14.214 --> 32:20.482
Because even if a guy doesn't want to do something, 
if he's placed in a position, most people can do the

32:14.214 --> 32:20.482
best they can with what they've got. And so I think 
that not only would we have a better military, But I

32:24.875 --> 32:32.426
think you'd have more patriotism in this country 
because more people would be touched with it in a

32:24.875 --> 32:32.426
direct basis. Wealthy families may go for 
generations without ever having a member of their

32:32.446 --> 32:37.894
family ever serve a day in the military. That's 
criminal. What a privilege that they've missed.

32:42.861 --> 32:44.083
What about women? Do you think women in America 
should also serve in the military? In today's

32:47.608 --> 32:48.869
environment, I do. I think they should be drafted 
right along with men. And here, once again, you've

32:53.292 --> 32:57.899
got the question of who you draft. But we've always 
had that question, and it worked relatively well.

33:02.005 --> 33:03.047
You register everyone. And the lottery wasn't a 
bad way to do it. At least you get a good cross

33:07.093 --> 33:08.876
section. I feel that whether anybody wants to 
admit it or not, there are differences between men

33:10.458 --> 33:18.290
and women. I think in combat situations where you 
are living off the land without any latrine

33:20.900 --> 33:28.410
facilities or anything like that, it would be a 
mistake to put women into a combat situation. But

33:28.430 --> 33:32.595
there are lots of ways they can serve without being 
in the trenches on the front lines. In other words,

33:33.316 --> 33:45.993
do you agree with old Harry Truman's idea of the 
universal military training, that everyone,

33:33.316 --> 33:45.993
when they turn a certain age, 18 or 19, should have a 
year or two of some sort of service to the country?

33:46.954 --> 33:49.658
Or do you think that's too broad and too expensive? 
I would like to see it, but I think from a practical

33:50.313 --> 33:55.438
standpoint that that would be too expensive. I 
feel that everyone should register, that there

33:56.459 --> 34:11.234
possibly should be a certain amount of 
indoctrination required in conjunction with

33:56.459 --> 34:11.234
that registration, maybe a half a day of some very 
basics about what our country is all about. And

34:12.315 --> 34:19.763
then if they're fortunate enough or unfortunate 
enough, depending on how they view it, to be

34:12.315 --> 34:19.763
selected for the draft, then I think that should be 
done. so that you've got a good cross-section of

34:20.249 --> 34:26.637
this country defending the country. And not only 
that individual, but also the impact that

34:26.657 --> 34:33.986
individual has on his immediate family and his 
neighbors and friends and what have you. There are

34:34.006 --> 34:44.519
parts of Houston that you could go into and 
probably go for 40 houses, and they don't have

34:34.006 --> 34:44.519
anybody in the military and never have had anybody 
in the military since the draft. It's not right.

34:49.605 --> 34:49.885
So... You probably didn't want to know that. I want 
all that. As a matter of fact, I have very similar

34:54.957 --> 34:59.247
feelings. Being a veteran, I have very similar 
feelings on that. And I want to know this. There's

35:05.727 --> 35:07.810
another thing that I'd like to know. Sometimes, 
especially during the Vietnamese War, a lot of

35:07.850 --> 35:15.402
journalists said that there was such a thing as a 
military mentality. That was usually the term

35:15.783 --> 35:20.230
they used, that there was a way that the military 
thinks about it. Well, you're both in an

35:20.250 --> 35:28.103
institution and you're in another institution, 
the military, and I was wondering what you

35:20.250 --> 35:28.103
thought. Is there such a thing as a military 
mentality, and if so, what is it? I would think that

35:33.605 --> 35:49.464
if there is such a thing, that it would be a normal 
outgrowth of having been in a profession for a

35:33.605 --> 35:49.464
number of years in which you tend to accept the 
policies that are established by the military

35:33.605 --> 35:49.464
establishment as your own policies. I don't mean 
that people follow the party line right down to the

35:50.806 --> 35:59.697
nth degree, but chances are,

36:01.347 --> 36:11.740
Just like here, if Dr. Vannevar wants to do 
something, I don't have any strong objections not

36:01.347 --> 36:11.740
to do it, well then I adopt that as my policy because 
I'm supporting Dr. Vannevar and his ideas. The

36:12.341 --> 36:13.682
same thing is true in the military. I would say that

36:14.744 --> 36:22.073
you wouldn't find any difference in the military 
way of responding to suggestions and policies

36:22.492 --> 36:28.099
adopted by their superiors than you would find in 
the civilian sector. OK. And I wanted to ask you

36:28.119 --> 36:32.704
another question on that, as far as advancement. 
You've advanced substantially in both the

36:32.885 --> 36:39.192
military and in university. And before that, you 
were for Sears and Roebuck. Now I'm wondering, and

36:42.676 --> 36:46.981
for a while you even had your own company. I'm 
wondering if it's the same type

36:51.972 --> 36:59.179
characteristics that make someone a success in 
the military as in private or in public

36:51.972 --> 36:59.179
institutions? Absolutely. I don't think there's 
any difference. I think it's a situation of

37:01.722 --> 37:08.369
learning a skill, filling the squares, doing the 
job. But to me, I think that success in private

37:08.389 --> 37:21.102
business, success within a corporate structure, 
or success in the military, assuming that you're

37:08.389 --> 37:21.102
doing the technical side of your job, is primarily 
a matter of attitude and personality, human

37:21.655 --> 37:27.100
relations. Those things are 80% of it. Only 20% of 
it is skill and knowledge, in my opinion. And

37:34.226 --> 37:36.188
that's true in the military or wherever you go.

37:39.791 --> 37:49.840
When you think back on your career, which of course 
isn't completed yet, but when you think back on it,

37:39.791 --> 37:49.840
do you see yourself now as ambitious?

37:54.173 --> 37:54.974
That's a hard one. Sure is. I don't see myself as 
ambitious for ambition's sake to attain a

37:57.137 --> 38:14.702
certain, in other words, I've never had the 
ambition to be a two-star general for the sake of

37:57.137 --> 38:14.702
just saying, look at me, I'm a two-star general. 
I'm ambitious from the point that I like

38:15.643 --> 38:19.309
responsibility. I like accomplishing work. I 
like delegating and working through people. And

38:23.975 --> 38:34.991
I'd be less than honest if I didn't say that I like a 
certain amount of authority to be able to direct

38:23.975 --> 38:34.991
things and make things happen that I think should 
happen. But as a result of doing these things, if

38:36.072 --> 38:42.782
promotions and recognition come as a result, then 
that's great. But that's not the primary goal. The

38:46.087 --> 38:52.716
goal is to do something, hopefully that would be a 
benefit to whatever organization I'm talking

38:46.087 --> 38:52.716
about, whether it be the military, whether it be 
Texas A&M, whether it be my church, whether it be my

38:53.050 --> 38:57.195
family. Do the best you can with the jobs at hand, 
and then if recognition and promotions come, well

38:58.757 --> 39:04.583
and good. Well, did you leave on the way up the 
ladder then to success, did you leave that

39:04.904 --> 39:19.340
advancement to fate or luck, or do you think that 
that advancement was because you accomplished

39:04.904 --> 39:19.340
those individual tasks? I think I think the 
accomplishment of individual tasks was only part

39:21.265 --> 39:26.893
of it. I think the secret to my advancement and the 
secret to almost anyone's advancement

39:28.275 --> 39:47.982
has a whole lot to do with proximity to power 
sources, knowing people that are in a position to

39:28.275 --> 39:47.982
promote you, knowing people that are in a position 
to recommend you for certain jobs, doing a job that

39:49.784 --> 39:57.152
they become aware of, whether it's from their own 
initiative or whether you make sure that they are

39:49.784 --> 39:57.152
aware of what you're doing. I have no big hang up 
with blowing your own horn, as long as it's done for

39:58.354 --> 40:08.526
the proper motives and as long as it's honest and 
true. As long as you're not inflating yourself.

40:13.051 --> 40:13.311
That's right. That's right. Of course, we're on 
another thin sheet of ice here. That's true. On

40:17.054 --> 40:27.030
what is the question between realistically 
saying, here's what I have achieved, and then

40:17.054 --> 40:27.030
inflating what you've done and boasting. That's 
right. It's a matter of personal

40:28.112 --> 40:36.646
integrity as to whether you do that or not. Chances 
are you could. But almost always, when you inflate

40:40.055 --> 40:43.079
something, it's going to catch up with you. And our 
superiors should see it. That's true. But I would

40:47.804 --> 40:58.036
think that not being afraid to speak up, to 
introduce yourself six, eight, 10 times if

40:47.804 --> 40:58.036
necessary, until somebody learns your name. I got 
real tickled at the last board meeting. I was to

41:04.163 --> 41:09.910
give a report to the board on the parking 
conditions over and around the vet college. And

41:11.341 --> 41:14.625
I've only been a vice president since last 
October, so I don't know all the board. Well, I know

41:14.705 --> 41:16.767
all the board members, but they all don't know me. 
So I've had a great deal of difficulty in the few

41:17.348 --> 41:21.893
times that they are on campus for them to learn my 
name. And most of them know my face and know that I'm

41:22.554 --> 41:27.440
connected with the physical plant in some way or 
the police, but they don't know my name. So

41:28.401 --> 41:41.196
finally, I'd introduce myself to Mr.

41:28.401 --> 41:41.196
Joe Richardson, who's the chairman of our 
building committee a number of times, and just a

41:28.401 --> 41:41.196
super guy. And so it came to my part on the program. 
He says, OK. He says, I've asked Dr. Vandiver to put

41:45.036 --> 41:53.285
together a report on parking conditions and a 
petition that some of the vet students had put

41:45.036 --> 41:53.285
together for us. And he says, and he's asked Chuck 
to give the report. And I thought, thank goodness.

41:56.849 --> 41:58.931
Boy, he finally learned my name. He says, and now to 
give the report is Chuck McCandless. So I thought,

42:02.775 --> 42:04.858
well, I'm halfway home. So Dr. Vandiver corrected 
him. And then he later on told me he's sure sorry

42:05.899 --> 42:09.443
that he tried to remember my name as Cargill. But 
anyway. There's all the board members sitting

42:11.433 --> 42:18.342
around, so I'll probably be Chuck McCandless to 
them for the rest of their life because, of course,

42:11.433 --> 42:18.342
Chuck has appeared before the board a number of 
times. But name recognition is so important.

42:23.769 --> 42:27.854
Letting people know that you want to do what you can 
to help them with their programs. If you can help

42:29.196 --> 42:35.103
enough other people get what they want, then 
you'll get what you want. It's a service-oriented

42:35.223 --> 42:41.271
type philosophy, but you've also got to be a little 
bit pushy in letting people know that, Hey, if

42:41.892 --> 42:44.515
there's something else I can do to help you with 
that, let me know. Be willing to accept the

42:45.256 --> 42:50.182
responsibility and help the guy with his 
problems, and he'll love you for it. And he'll

42:51.764 --> 42:52.766
promote you for it. And it's something that you're 
accomplishing your objectives to, and that's to

42:54.948 --> 42:59.775
be of more service to whatever organization it may 
be. I want to talk about that and accomplishments.

43:04.775 --> 43:16.833
When you look back on your career in the military, 
and of course this is a question that's premature

43:04.775 --> 43:16.833
because you might be at the point of your career 
where you're going to have the most impact on the

43:04.775 --> 43:16.833
Air Force. But when you look back at your career, 
what do you see as accomplishments

43:17.574 --> 43:27.188
in the reserves? And I also want you to think, was 
there anything that you thought were

43:28.449 --> 43:32.976
shortcomings? I would think that probably the 
period of time, not a specific instance, but a

43:34.053 --> 43:52.514
period of time in which a number of things happened 
that I point to with pride more than just about any

43:34.053 --> 43:52.514
other, was the time that I served as a full colonel 
at 10th Air Force Headquarters as Director of

43:34.053 --> 43:52.514
Logistics Plan for the 10th Air Force. During that 
period of time, we performed what we call staff

43:53.415 --> 43:59.062
assistance visits to our units, which were all 
over the United States. We had put together a team

43:59.803 --> 44:01.765
from the headquarters. And as a full colonel, I was 
frequently the team chief, which is another way of

44:02.167 --> 44:08.294
saying the highest-ranking guy in charge of the 
team. Anywhere from 20 to 40 people would come on an

44:09.135 --> 44:13.140
airplane, and we'd go visit our units. They called 
them inspections, and that's really what they

44:14.001 --> 44:16.184
were. But we didn't like the word inspection. We 
called them staff assistance visits. And they say

44:21.029 --> 44:29.980
the two biggest lies ever told in the Air Force is 
when the team gets off, the team chief said, we're

44:21.029 --> 44:29.980
here to help you, and the guy that you're visiting 
said, we're glad to see you. And those are the two

44:30.871 --> 44:32.634
biggest lies I've ever told. But anyway. But 
during that period of time, when I was team chief,

44:34.838 --> 44:44.575
visiting these units all over the United States, I 
consider that to be my most productive time as far

44:34.838 --> 44:44.575
as making a contribution. Because, of course, 
those of us that were specialists in certain areas

44:44.595 --> 44:55.815
could go in and look at their records, look at their 
programs, look at their in-commission rates and

44:44.595 --> 44:55.815
so forth. check some of their supplies to see how 
long it's been since certain wear date items like

44:56.420 --> 45:04.291
rubber can't stay in a kit too long because it gets 
hard and you've got to replace it. And those kinds

45:05.192 --> 45:11.340
of things, I feel we've really made a contribution 
toward the readiness of the reserve program. But I

45:11.360 --> 45:15.265
look at that as my most productive time as far as 
making a contribution. When you become a general

45:16.147 --> 45:20.372
officer, you've got to define the word general. It 
means a general officer as opposed to a specialist

45:20.993 --> 45:24.638
officer. Up to that point, you're a specialist in 
some field. You become a general officer. You

45:29.025 --> 45:29.967
could be in personnel. You could be in supply. You 
